Open Science at the Core of Libraries

Before we learn what is Open Science

Science is the process approaching truth, but scientific knowledge is a product of social collaboration and its ownership belongs to the community.

Scientifice knowledge is original scientific research results, raw data and metadata, source materials, digital representations of pictorial and graphical materials and scholarly multimedia material(Berlin Declaration, 2010)

What is open science

a new approach to the scientific process based on cooperative work and new ways of diffusing knowledge by using digital technologies and new collaborative tools(European Commission, 2016b:33)

to make the primary outputs of publicly funded research results publications and the research data publicly accessible in digital format with no or minimal restriction (OECD, 2015:7)

Even though, especially for the library and information domain, the focus is usually placed on two of these movements: Open Research Data and Open Access to scientific publications

Five Open Science schools of thought (Fecher and Friesike, 2014)

  • The infrastructure school concerned with the technological architecture. (Manage research materials and data in accessible reporsitory)
  • The public school concerned with the accessibility of knowledge creation. (Policy encourages open science practices)
  • The measurement school concerned with alternative impact measurement. (Alternative IF reveals the contribution)
  • The democratic school concerned with access to knowledge. (Share the values through education)
  • The pragmatic school concerned with collaborative research. (Promote a culture of open science)

What are the benefits of Open Science?

Supportive Factors for Developing Sciences(OECD, 2015:18)

  • Efficiency
  • Quality and integrity Check the Economist
  • Economic benefits
  • Innovation and knowledge transfer
  • Public disclosure and engagement
  • Global benefits

What are the challenges for Open Science?

Challenges

  • Socio-cultural researchers concern: benefits for competitors
  • Technological transparent workflow? My blog posts about registered reports and academic journals
  • Political no supportive policy
  • Organisational institutional deterrent over individual incentive
  • Economic short of funding, highly charaged OA fee
  • Legal Copyright issue

Boundaries(The Royal Society, 2012:44)

  • Commercial interests and economic benefits
    • Data ownership and the exercise of Intellectual Property rights
    • Public-private partnerships
    • Opening up commercial information in the public interest
  • Privacy
  • Security and safety

Strategies (European Commission, 2016b:45)

4 levels: people -> infrastructure -> policies -> economic investment

  1. Fostering and creating incentives for Open Science: Ph.D program for the imrpovement of research qualit`
  2. Removing barriers to Open Science
  3. Open access policies
  4. Developing research infrastructures for Open Science: DataWiz
  5. Embedding Open Science in society as a socio-economic driver: Build bridges to citizen science

free access to scientific knowledge for everybody(Sitek and Bertelmann, 2014)

What is in Open Science for Libraries?

Supporters of Open Access and Open Data (European Commission, 2012).

In open science practices, scitentists have to manage their works open and reproducible.

Enablers of Open Science Practices: Libraries have adapted their role and are now active in the preservation, curation, publication and dissemination of digital scientific materials, in the form of publications, data and other research-related content. Libraries and repositories constitute the physical infrastructure that allows scientists to share use and reuse the outcome of their work, and they have been essential in the creation of the Open Science movement (OECD, 2015).

How libraries can fulfill their role of enablers and have their say?

  1. Advocating and raising awareness
  2. Giving support to the infrastructures
  3. Contributing to the development of research data management (RDM) policies and strategies at their home institutions and carrying RDM themselves
  4. Training and supporting researchers
